2 major class are family size(4 classes) and education level(3 classes) There is no particular relationship between credit card expenditure and size of the family.

There is a slight increase in the expenditure of graduates compared to UG(Not significant)

There are UG who seem to earn more than graduates and Professionals. There appears to be no correlation between age and income and the data appears to be a cloud.

The relation between income and family appears to be small. Slight increase for size 2 and then decreases as size increases.

For zip code and income there are areas where the income is quite high and areas where it is significantly low. Credit card average expenditure and mortgage follows a similar trend. Family size is evenly spread. Correlation between zip code and personal loan is nearly zero. So dropping zip code until we get more evidence that people in certain areas purchase personal loan.

The relation between age and experience is nearly linear. So we can drop either one. Age has a slightly better negative correlation with personal loan No significant relation between personal loan and these two but extremely young or less experienced people don't purchase loan.

optimalF1 = 0
optimalTh = 0
thresholds[0:10]

    preds = np.where(model.predict_proba(X_train)[:,1] > th, 1, 0)
    f1Score = f1_score(y_train, preds)
    if(optimalF1 < f1Score):
        optimalF1 = f1Score
        optimalTh = th

Insights for Nave Bayes model:

  • Of the 1351 people who won't get the loan, the model is able to identify 1156 people
  • Of the 149 people who will get the loan, the model is able to identify 131 people
  • The model has incorrectly identified 195 who won't be getting the loan as people who will get the loan.
  • The model has incorrectly identified 18 people who will be getting the loan as people who won't get it.
  • Of the times the model predicts a person will get the loan, only 40% is correct.
  • Of the times the person does get a loan, the model is able to predict 88% of the time

Final Insights

  • KNN model has the highest accuracy at 95% and when it predicts a person will get a loan, it is correct 92% of the time and for all the people who get a loan, the model is able to predict them correctly 63% of the time.
  • Logistic regression has the second highest accuracy at 94% and when it predicts a person will get a loan, it is correct 74% of the time and for all the people who get a loan, the model is able to predict them correctly 70% of the time.
  • Nave Bayes has the lowest accuracy at 85% and when it predicts a person will get a loan, it is correct 40% of the time and for all the people who get a loan, the model is able to predict them correctly 88% of the time.
  • Based on the above conclusion and since the required model has to predict people who will actually get a loan better, the KNN model with the precision of 92% is the best model.
